    bodyMarkdown: `The war at Kurukshetra does not begin with an argument, or a throne, or even a family. It begins, if you follow the thread back far enough, with a king standing on a riverbank, agreeing to a condition he does not understand.

Shantanu is that king — ruler of the Kurus, of the city of Hastinapura, some three generations before the war that will end his line's quarrel. On the bank of the Ganga he meets a woman the epic simply calls the river itself, in the shape of a woman, and asks her to marry him. She agrees to one term: he must never question anything she does, never ask her why, and the day he does, she will leave. A man in love agrees to almost anything. Shantanu agrees to this.

Then the marriage delivers on its terms in the cruelest way it can. She bears him a son, carries the newborn to the water, and drowns him. Bound by his promise, Shantanu says nothing. She does it again. And again — seven sons, seven times carried to the river, while the king watches and holds his tongue, because the alternative is losing her. It is one of the harder things the epic asks you to sit with early on: a good man doing nothing, over and over, because he has bound himself to do nothing.

At the eighth child, he breaks. He seizes her arm and demands to know what kind of mother she is. And so, having lost her the moment he asked, she tells him — because now she is leaving anyway. She is Ganga. The seven sons were the Vasus, celestial beings condemned to be born as mortals under a curse; by drowning them at birth she was not killing them but freeing them, returning them at once to the life they had lost. This eighth one she cannot free the same way. He must live out a full mortal span. So she will take him, raise him, and one day return him grown.

She keeps that promise, which is more than can be said for most of the promises in this story. Years later she gives Shantanu back a young man — trained, learned, formidable, the finest prince the Kuru line has produced. His name is Devavrata. He is the rightful heir to Hastinapura, and everything about him says so. The epic wants you to notice how completely his future is assumed here, at the start — because the very next chapter is the story of him giving all of it away, on a riverbank not unlike this one, over another woman his father cannot stop wanting.`,
