    bodyMarkdown: `Some time after Ganga returns his son to him, Shantanu is out along another river when he catches the scent of something extraordinary — and follows it to Satyavati, a ferryman's daughter who works the crossing. He wants to marry her. It should be simple; he is the king. It is not simple, because her father has a price, and the price is the throne.

The ferryman will give his daughter only on one condition: that her sons, and not any other, will inherit Hastinapura. And Shantanu cannot agree, because he already has an heir — Devavrata, grown and returned and beyond reproach, the son Ganga raised for exactly this. To promise the throne to Satyavati's unborn children would be to disinherit the one child he has. So the king says nothing, and goes home, and does what his people have started to recognize as a family trait: he falls sick with a longing he refuses to explain.

It is Devavrata who drags it into the open. He notices his father wasting away, gets the truth out of the charioteer, and goes to the ferryman himself — not to plead, but to settle it. On the spot, he renounces the throne. He will never be king; Satyavati's sons will inherit. That should be enough. But the ferryman, thinking like a father, sees one flaw: Devavrata may give up his own claim, but what about *his* sons? A prince's children might one day look at the Kuru throne and remember whose it should have been.

So Devavrata closes that door too, with the sentence that reshapes the entire epic. He swears that he will never marry, never father a child, never leave descendants to contest anything — lifelong celibacy, on top of the crown already surrendered. The gods are said to have rained flowers on him for it, and to have given him the name he carries ever after: **Bhishma**, "the terrible one," not for cruelty but for the sheer terribleness of the oath. He is also granted, in some tellings, a boon that will matter enormously later — that death cannot take him until he himself consents to it.

It is worth being clear about what this vow actually costs, because the epic spends the next several generations paying the bill. To win his father one marriage, Bhishma has sterilized the main line of the dynasty and made himself its permanent, childless guardian — a man of immense capability with no stake of his own in who sits on the throne, only a vow to protect whoever does. Satyavati becomes queen. Her sons will inherit, as promised. And that is precisely the trouble the next chapter opens on: those sons, and how quickly and badly the line Bhishma bought so dearly begins to fail.`,
