    bodyMarkdown: `Satyavati bears Shantanu two sons, and the throne Bhishma bought with his vow passes to them in turn. It does not go well. The elder, Chitrangada, is killed young in a fight with a rival of the same name before he leaves any heir. That leaves the younger, Vichitravirya — still a boy, and by every account a frail one — as the only living thread of the entire Kuru line. Bhishma, who cannot take the throne himself and cannot father a replacement, is left to keep that one frail thread from snapping.

His solution is to find the boy a wife, or several. He hears that the king of Kashi is holding a swayamvara — the ceremony where a princess chooses her own husband from an assembled field of suitors — for his three daughters: Amba, Ambika, and Ambalika. Bhishma does not send a suitor. He goes himself, and carries all three princesses off by force, on the old warrior's principle that a bride seized in strength is a legitimate prize. No one at the gathering can stop him. It is, on its own terms, a success: three brides delivered to Hastinapura for the survival of the dynasty.

It is also where the dynasty's survival collides with a person who did not consent to be a means to it. The eldest, Amba, tells Bhishma what he did not think to ask: she is already in love, promised in her own heart to King Salva, and had come to the swayamvara meaning to choose him. Bhishma, who at least respects the claim, releases her and sends her to Salva. But Salva will not have her back — she has been won and carried off by another man, and to his mind that is the end of it, whatever her wishes were. Rejected on both sides, belonging to no one because two men treated her as a thing to be won or declined, Amba is left with nothing but the question of whose fault it is.

She decides it is Bhishma's. And here the chain that runs the length of the epic pulls taut: Amba does not weep and vanish from the story. She devotes herself, with a patience that outlasts her own lifetime, to becoming the instrument of Bhishma's death — through years of austerity, through the boons those austerities win her, and finally through rebirth into the body of a warrior, Shikhandi, in whose presence Bhishma's vows will not let him fight. The old man who abducted her on the battlefield of a swayamvara will, decades on, lower his bow at her approach on the battlefield of Kurukshetra. The epic plants that seed here, quietly, and lets it grow.

Meanwhile the immediate crisis only deepens. Vichitravirya marries the two younger sisters, Ambika and Ambalika — and then dies, like his brother, without leaving a child. Bhishma has now abducted brides, made a lifelong enemy, and buried the last two heirs of the Kuru line, and the throne he swore to protect has no one left to sit on it at all. The line his vow was meant to secure is, for the second time in two generations, one death away from simply ending.`,
