    bodyMarkdown: `With both her sons dead childless and Bhishma immovable behind his vow, Satyavati is the one left holding the problem: a throne, two young widows, and no one to father the next king. She proposes the obvious solution of her age — that Bhishma set the vow aside and take his brother's widows to continue the line. Bhishma refuses. He will give up the sun's warmth and the earth's solidity before he gives up his word, he tells her; the vow does not bend for convenience, not even the survival of the dynasty. It is the first time in the story we see how absolute he is, and not the last time that absoluteness costs everyone around him.

So Satyavati turns to a secret she has carried since before her marriage. Long ago, before Shantanu, a sage had fathered a son on her — a son born and grown apart from the palace, now a formidable ascetic in his own right: **Vyasa**, the same sage whom tradition names as the composer of the Mahabharata itself. It is one of the epic's quiet audacities that the man said to have authored the whole poem also steps into it here, as a character, to keep its central family from dying out. Satyavati summons him and asks him to do what Bhishma will not: father heirs on the two widowed queens, by the old custom of *niyoga*, in which a kinsman raises children for a man who has died without them.

Vyasa agrees, but warns that the mother must meet him without flinching, and that whatever she feels in that moment will leave its mark on the child. The warning is the whole point of the chapter. Ambika, sent to him first, shuts her eyes against the sight of the rough, austere sage — and bears a son, Dhritarashtra, strong and able but born blind. Ambalika, sent next, goes pale with fear and holds her ground without closing her eyes — and bears Pandu, sound but born with a pallor that gives him his name. Asked for one more child, Ambika cannot face it again and sends a serving-maid in her place; the maid, expecting nothing and fearing nothing, receives the sage calmly — and bears Vidura, clear-eyed and whole and, by common account, the wisest of the three.

The three brothers who will govern the next chapter of the dynasty are, in other words, sorted at the moment of their conception into exactly the roles they will spend their lives inside. Dhritarashtra, the eldest and the strongest, is passed over for the throne because a king in this world cannot be blind — a disqualification he never stops resenting, and never stops trying to correct through his sons. Pandu, sound enough to rule, takes the crown his elder brother cannot. And Vidura, wisest of them all, is barred from it entirely, because his mother was a maid — left to serve as counsellor and conscience to a court that will overrule him at every decisive turn.

It is a strange, human, quietly ominous way to found a royal generation: no divine coronation, no clean line of succession, just three frightened or fearless women and the children their fear or fearlessness shaped. The throne Bhishma's vow was meant to protect is filled again — but filled with a blind king who feels cheated, a pale king who will not live to raise his sons, and a wise man forbidden to rule. Everything the war will eventually be fought over is already sitting in that nursery. The next chapter lets those three brothers grow up and start making the choices that turn all of it into a quarrel with no way out but Kurukshetra.`,
