    bodyMarkdown: `In the forest, Pandu turns the problem over and over. A king without a son is a dead end, curse or no curse, and the curse has closed the ordinary road entirely. It is Kunti who finally opens the other one, by telling him the secret she has kept since girlhood.

Years before her marriage, Kunti had done a kindness for the volatile sage Durvasa, and he had rewarded her with a mantra: a formula that would summon any god she named, who would then give her a son. She had been a curious girl with a dangerous gift, and — the epic is unsparing about this — she had tried it once, to see if it worked. She called the sun god Surya, and it worked. A son was born to her, radiant, armoured from birth. Unmarried and afraid of the shame, she set the infant in a basket on a river and let the water take him. She has never spoken of him since, and she does not dwell on him now. But the mantra is still hers, and it is the way out of Pandu's curse: children fathered not by him, but summoned, and raised as his own.

So, at Pandu's urging, she uses it deliberately this time. She calls Dharma, the god of righteousness, and bears Yudhishthira, marked from birth for truth and judgment. She calls Vayu, god of the wind, and bears Bhima, enormous and unstoppable. She calls Indra, king of the gods, and bears Arjuna, on whom the whole future of the family's arms will rest. Three sons, three gods, three of the qualities the coming war will demand — and then Pandu asks for more, and Kunti refuses to overuse a power she respects too much to treat as a well. Instead she teaches the mantra to Madri, once, and Madri — thinking cannily — summons the twin Ashwins in a single invocation and bears twins: Nakula and Sahadeva. Five sons, in all. The Pandavas.

They are, in the most literal sense the epic will allow, sons of the gods — and yet the story never lets that make them more than human. They are raised in a forest hermitage as ordinary boys with an extraordinary father-problem, and the divinity in their blood mostly shows up later as competence under pressure rather than as magic. What matters here is simply that Pandu has heirs, the line is secure, and for a brief window the exiled king is almost happy.

The window closes the way the curse always meant it to. One spring day, with his guard down and his wife beside him, Pandu forgets — just for a moment, just long enough — and reaches for Madri. The curse takes him instantly, exactly as the sage promised. Madri, convinced she has killed her husband by not stopping him, cannot live with it; when the pyre is built, she climbs onto it after him, leaving her twins to Kunti. And so Kunti comes down out of the mountains at last, a widow with five boys who are not all hers, walking back toward the city her husband gave up — toward Hastinapura, and the hundred cousins already waiting there.`,
