    bodyMarkdown: `While Pandu was in the forest fathering sons by summoned gods, his blind brother's household was struggling with a stranger problem: a pregnancy that would not end. Gandhari, behind her self-imposed blindfold, had conceived early and then simply stayed pregnant — a year, and then longer — while word reached the forest that Kunti had already borne her first son. The epic reads Gandhari's long ordeal partly as grief and partly as omen: something about this birth is not going to be ordinary.

At last, in despair, she strikes her own womb, and delivers not a child but a hard, lifeless mass of flesh. It is the sage Vyasa — the same Vyasa who fathered her husband, and who keeps stepping in whenever this family reaches an impasse — who tells her not to throw it away. On his instruction the mass is divided into a hundred and one pieces and kept in pots of cool ghee, and from those pots, in time, come a hundred sons and a single daughter, Duhshala. The eldest to emerge, and the first of the Kauravas, is Duryodhana.

His birth is the hinge the whole epic turns on, and it is drowned in bad omens. Jackals howl at the edges of the city; the infant's first cry comes out like a donkey's bray; the sky darkens. The court's wise men — Vidura foremost among them — read the signs plainly and give the blind king plain advice: this child is marked to be the ruin of the dynasty, and for the good of the ninety-nine others and the whole Kuru line, he should be given up. It is a terrible thing to ask of a father, and the text does not pretend otherwise. But it is asked, clearly, by the people whose job is to see what the king cannot.

And Dhritarashtra cannot do it. The blind king, who has spent his life feeling cheated of a throne, cannot bring himself to give up his firstborn son — the one thing that is unarguably his. He keeps the child. It is the first of a long series of moments where Dhritarashtra knows the right course, is told the right course, and chooses his son instead; the epic will return to this fault in him again and again, until it has consumed everyone. Love, in this story, is rarely the thing that saves people. Here it is the first push toward the war.

So the stage fills out. In the forest, Kunti is on her way home with five boys who have no father. In the city, a hundred brothers are growing up around one who was warned against and kept anyway. Very soon these two sets of cousins will be handed to the same teachers, raised in the same courtyards, measured against each other daily — and the next chapter is what happens when you put them in the same training ground and hand them all weapons.`,
