    bodyMarkdown: `Kunti brings the five Pandavas back to Hastinapura, and the court accepts them as princes of the line — which means that from boyhood, the five and the hundred are raised together, in the same yards, under the same eyes. It does not go well, and the epic is honest that the fault is not all on one side. Bhima, gifted with more raw strength than any child should have, uses it the way strong children do: he bullies the Kaurava boys, ducks them in the river, shakes them out of trees. The hundred nurse it, and Duryodhana nurses it hardest.

Duryodhana's answer is not a boyhood answer. He poisons Bhima at a feast, binds his unconscious body, and throws him into the river to drown — the first attempt on a Pandava life, made while they are all still children. Bhima survives, by the epic's account carried down to the realm of the serpents and returned even stronger than before, and comes home as if nothing happened. But something has happened: the enmity is now real, and lethal, and mutual, years before anyone speaks of a throne. The war does not begin at Kurukshetra. It begins in a courtyard, between cousins, with poison.

Into this, Bhishma brings a teacher — Drona, a brahmin master of arms who takes charge of every prince in the city, Pandava and Kaurava alike. Under him the boys become warriors, and one becomes something more: Arjuna, whose focus and hunger for the craft set him apart so completely that Drona comes to love him, and promises to make him the finest archer in the world. It is a promise a teacher should perhaps not make, because it commits him to keeping everyone else below his favourite — and the epic tests that commitment almost at once.

A boy named Ekalavya, born to a forest tribe and turned away by Drona for his low birth, refuses to accept that the knowledge is closed to him. He builds a clay image of Drona, treats it as his teacher, and trains before it alone until he can outshoot the trained princes of Hastinapura. When Drona discovers this — a student he never taught, better than the pupil he swore to keep supreme — he does not celebrate the talent. He invokes the oldest custom of teaching, the fee a student owes his master, and asks Ekalavya for it: the thumb of his right hand, the archer's thumb. And Ekalavya, who was never even granted the teaching, cuts it off and gives it, without a word of protest. It is one of the passages the epic offers without softening, and it sits like a stone: the price of protecting privilege, paid by the one person with the least.

All of this comes to a head at a public tournament, where Drona presents his pupils to the whole court and the city to show what they can do. The Pandavas and Kauravas display their skills in turn, and Arjuna, as arranged, is the star of it — until the demonstration is interrupted by a young man no one invited, who walks into the arena and announces that he can do everything Arjuna just did. The next chapter is who he is, and what Duryodhana does the instant he sees him.`,
