    bodyMarkdown: `The young man who interrupts the tournament makes good on his boast. Feat for feat, he matches everything Arjuna has just performed, in front of the same court that had come to crown Arjuna the best. His name is Karna, and from the moment he enters, the epic makes sure the reader knows what the arena does not: this is Kunti's firstborn, the radiant, armour-born son she summoned from the sun god as a frightened girl and set adrift on a river. The infant in the basket has grown up — found and raised by a charioteer and his wife — and walked back into his own family as a stranger.

The arena, of course, knows none of that. It sees only a newcomer challenging a prince, and the challenge runs into a wall the moment it is issued. To duel Arjuna, Karna must be Arjuna's equal in rank; a prince does not cross weapons with a commoner. Asked to name his royal line, Karna cannot — he is the son of Adhiratha the charioteer, or so everyone including Karna believes — and the assembly, which a moment ago was watching a marvel, turns and laughs at him. It is the wound the epic keeps pressing for the rest of Karna's life: not a lack of ability, which he has in abundance, but a birth that the world will never let his ability outrun.

And then Duryodhana, watching, sees in a single instant both an insult he can answer and an ally he can own. He rises and, on his own authority, crowns Karna king of Anga then and there — conjuring the royal rank the rules demand, and making the duel legitimate. The gesture is calculated and it is also, in its way, genuine: Duryodhana lifts up the one man in the arena whom everyone else has just humiliated, and Karna never forgets it. From that day he is Duryodhana's, completely and to the death — the greatest warrior the Kaurava side will ever field, bound by a debt of gratitude rather than blood or ambition.

The tragedy the epic is quietly assembling is now nearly complete, and only two people can see it. Kunti, watching from the stands, recognizes the armour and the radiance and knows exactly who this humiliated stranger is — and says nothing, because to speak is to unravel her own life and her sons' standing. So she keeps the secret she has kept since the riverbank, and lets her eldest son be adopted, in front of her, into the cause that exists to destroy her other five. The man Duryodhana raises up to break the Pandavas is the Pandavas' own eldest brother.

That single buried fact — Karna's birth, known to Kunti and Krishna and almost no one else — sits under everything that follows, from the dice game to the last day of the war, when Arjuna finally kills the challenger from the tournament without ever being told, until too late, that he was killing his brother. The backstory is now told. The pieces are all on the board: a blind king who cannot deny his son, a hundred cousins and five, a teacher's favourite and a charioteer's son, an old vow and a rigged future. What turns them from a rivalry into a war is a game of dice — and that is where the next act begins.`,
