    bodyMarkdown: `The trouble with the Pandavas, from Duryodhana's side of it, is that people like them. As the cousins come of age, the city and the elders begin to speak of Yudhishthira — the eldest, the lawful son of the crown Pandu once wore — as the natural heir, and every sign of that preference lands on Duryodhana as a theft in progress. He goes to his father with it, and his father, who has never in his life been able to refuse this son anything, listens.

So a plan is made that wears the face of a kindness. The Pandavas and Kunti are invited to travel to Varanavata for a festival — a pleasant town, an honour, nothing to suspect. What waits for them there is a newly built palace, raised for their comfort by Duryodhana's agent Purochana, and constructed out of the most flammable materials that can be disguised as luxury: lac, resin, dried hemp, oil-soaked timber. It is a house built to become a fire, with the guests asleep inside it, and to leave behind only the kind of accident no one can be blamed for.

They are not caught unprepared, because Vidura will not let them be. The wise half-brother who has warned this court at every turn warns it again — but carefully, in a riddling speech at the gate that only Yudhishthira is meant to understand, about the rat that survives by digging and the fire that cannot burn what has already made its exit. A trusted miner arrives soon after and digs them a tunnel out beneath the house, and the Pandavas live in the trap for a while as if they suspect nothing, waiting for the right night.

When it comes, the epic hands the reader a passage it does not soften. The Pandavas set the fire themselves, on their own terms rather than Purochana's — and in the burning house, by the account the text gives, are also a woman of the forest and her five sons, who had come to a feast and fallen asleep drunk. Their bodies, six of them, are found in the ashes and taken for Kunti and her five. The Pandavas' escape is bought, in part, with lives that were not theirs to spend, and the epic lets that sit uncomfortably rather than pretending the righteous side kept its hands clean.

By morning, Varanavata is mourning a royal family, and Duryodhana, hundreds of miles away, is quietly, enormously relieved. The Pandavas are dead; the succession is settled; the problem is solved. And the problem, of course, is not dead at all — it is walking south through the forest in the matted hair and rough cloth of wandering brahmins, five brothers and their mother, free for the first time in their lives precisely because the world believes they no longer exist. What they walk toward, in the next chapter, is a contest for a bride they have no idea is about to remake their entire future.`,
