    bodyMarkdown: `Moving through the countryside as anonymous brahmins, the Pandavas hear of a swayamvara being held in Panchala, and go — partly as beggars go anywhere there will be a crowd and a feast, partly because the bride is already famous. She is Draupadi, also called Krishnaa, and her origin is as charged as anything in the epic: she and her brother Dhrishtadyumna were born not from a womb but from their father Drupada's sacrificial fire, each brought into the world for a purpose. Dhrishtadyumna was born to kill Drona, an old enemy of Drupada's. Draupadi was born, the fire-priests said, to turn the course of the age.

The test Drupada sets is deliberately close to impossible: a massive bow few can even lift, a target set high and turning, to be pierced through a small aperture — in most tellings, the eye of a revolving fish, sighted by its reflection in a dish of water below. King after king rises, strains at the bow, and fails. Karna, present as ever at Duryodhana's side, comes forward and — by the version the epic most often tells — is stopped at the threshold by Draupadi herself, who will not wed a charioteer's son; another wound laid on the pile he already carries. And then a brahmin no one knows steps out of the watching crowd, lifts the bow as though it were ordinary, and puts the arrow through the mark.

It is Arjuna, of course, and the disguise does not survive the shot for long. The brothers take Draupadi back to the potter's hut where they are lodging, and here the epic turns on a single unthinking sentence. They call in to their mother that they have brought back something wonderful; Kunti, busy and not yet looking, gives the answer a mother gives to five sons who share everything — that they must share it equally among themselves. The word is out before she sees that the "something" is a woman, and in the moral world of the epic a mother's instruction, once spoken, is not lightly unsaid.

What follows is one of the passages the Mahabharata argues with itself about, openly. Draupadi as wife to all five brothers is unusual enough that the characters inside the story debate whether it can be right — Drupada objects, the elders deliberate, and the resolution rests partly on Kunti's word being binding and partly on assurances that this marriage is sanctioned by more than accident. The epic does not smooth it into something ordinary; it lets the strangeness stand, and lets Draupadi become the one wife of five husbands, bound to the center of the story she was born to turn.

For Drupada, the discovery that his daughter's brahmin husband is in fact Arjuna — that the Pandavas are alive — turns disappointment into triumph. Overnight he has gone from marrying his daughter to a beggar to allying his kingdom with the rightful heirs of Hastinapura, five formidable warriors the Kaurava court believes dead. The secret cannot hold now, and it does not: word travels north that the fire at Varanavata took someone, but not the Pandavas. In Hastinapura, Duryodhana's settled world comes undone, and the elders face a question they can no longer avoid — what to do with cousins who are alive, wronged, and now backed by Panchala. The next chapter is the uneasy answer they reach, and how quickly the Pandavas turn it into something that makes Duryodhana's envy unbearable.`,
