    relatedEventSlugs: ["the-rajasuya"],
    bodyMarkdown: `With the Pandavas alive and Panchala behind them, Hastinapura cannot simply wish them gone again. Bhishma, Drona, and Vidura press the blind king toward the only settlement that keeps the peace: give the Pandavas their share. Dhritarashtra agrees, and the kingdom is partitioned — but the partition is itself a slight. The Kauravas keep Hastinapura and the settled, prosperous heart of the realm; the Pandavas are handed Khandavaprastha, a tract of arid scrub and old forest with nothing on it. It is technically half a kingdom and practically an insult.

Before the wasteland becomes a city, it becomes a fire. In one of the epic's stranger episodes, Arjuna and Krishna help the fire-god Agni burn the vast Khandava forest that covered the land, holding off Indra himself and the storm he sends to quench it — and the two of them come out of that burning permanently armed: Arjuna receives the celestial bow Gandiva and a pair of quivers whose arrows never run dry, the weapons that will carry him through every battle to come, and Krishna the spinning discus, the Sudarshana. One life is deliberately spared from the flames — Maya, an asura craftsman of genius, whose gratitude will soon rebuild the very land he was pulled out of.

It is in these same Indraprastha years that the Pandavas' bond with Krishna deepens into blood. Bound by a self-imposed penance — he had broken the brothers' compact over Draupadi, and sentenced himself to a year's wandering for it — Arjuna travels far and comes at last to Krishna's city of Dwarka, where he loses his heart to Krishna's own sister, Subhadra. Krishna favours the match; his elder brother Balarama, inclining toward Duryodhana as a groom, does not. So with Krishna's quiet blessing Arjuna does the thing the age allows a warrior in love to do — he carries Subhadra off, with her own consent and, by many tellings, her own hand on the chariot's reins. Balarama's fury is talked down by Krishna, the marriage stands, and it will matter more than anyone yet knows: Subhadra bears Arjuna a son, Abhimanyu, and through Abhimanyu's own child the Kuru line will one day survive the war that is still a lifetime off.

What the Pandavas make of the cleared land is the turn of the chapter. With Krishna's help and the labour of Maya, the architect spared from the Khandava fire, they raise on that ground a city so magnificent it takes a new name: Indraprastha, a capital to rival any in the world, crowned by an assembly hall full of Maya's craft, including illusions so precise that solid floors look like water and pools of water look like polished stone. Yudhishthira rules justly; his brothers ride out and bring the surrounding kings under his sway — though not before the one rival who might have blocked it all, the mighty Jarasandha of Magadha, is drawn by Krishna into a wrestling match with Bhima and killed; and at the height of it Yudhishthira undertakes the Rajasuya, the great imperial sacrifice by which a king is acknowledged as paramount over other kings. It is the Pandavas at their zenith — rich, honoured, and, for once, unambiguously winning.

At the sacrifice, the first honour is given to Krishna, and when the king Shishupala rises to object and pours out insult after insult, Krishna kills him on the spot — a reminder threaded through these triumphant chapters that Krishna's presence is never merely ceremonial. But the moment the epic really wants is smaller and more human, and it belongs to Duryodhana, who has come as a guest to watch his cousins crowned in glory. Walking through Maya's illusion-hall, he misreads it exactly as it was built to be misread: he gathers his robes to cross what he takes for water and finds solid floor, then steps confidently onto what he takes for floor and falls into a pool. And someone laughs. In the most repeated version it is Draupadi, from a gallery above, calling him a blind son of a blind king — the cruelest possible thing to say in that court, and the one that lodges deepest.

He goes home poisoned by it. Everything he has just seen — the city, the sacrifice, the wealth, the wife who laughed — becomes a single unbearable fact: the cousins he tried to burn alive are not merely alive but exalted above him, and he cannot stand in the world while that is true. He says as much to his uncle Shakuni, and Shakuni, who has nursed his own long grudge against this dynasty, offers the tool he has been sharpening all along. Not war — the Pandavas are too strong, and would win. Something quieter, that turns their own virtue against them.

Shakuni's proposal is a game of dice. Yudhishthira, for all his righteousness — or precisely because of it — holds to a code in which a challenge to play cannot be honourably refused, and Shakuni has never in his life lost at dice he controls. The plan needs only the blind king's blessing to make the invitation official, and the blind king, asked by the son he cannot deny, gives it. The trap that the last several chapters have been walking toward is now set, baited with nothing more than Yudhishthira's sense of honour. The next chapter is the game itself.`,
