    relatedEventSlugs: ["game-of-dice"],
    bodyMarkdown: `The invitation comes dressed as friendship: a hall newly built at Hastinapura, a game among kinsmen, the courtesy of a visit. Yudhishthira understands well enough what it is, and comes anyway, because in the code he holds himself to, a summons to play cannot be declined without dishonour — and Shakuni has built the entire trap out of that single scruple. Yudhishthira will not cheat, will not walk away, and will not stop while there is a stake left to lose. His opponent across the board is Shakuni, throwing on Duryodhana's behalf with dice that do not fail him.

He loses, and having lost, he keeps playing. First the wealth — gold, jewels, herds. Then the land, and the city, and the kingdom he built out of a wasteland. Then, when there is nothing outside himself left to wager, he begins staking people: his brothers, one by one, Nakula and Sahadeva and Arjuna and Bhima, each named and lost like a coin. Then himself. And then, with even his own person forfeit, he stakes the last thing the table will let him name — Draupadi, wife to all five, and loses her too. The epic watches this with something like horror at its own hero: the most truthful man in the story, undone not by a vice he hides but by a virtue he cannot switch off.

What happens next is the wound the whole war will be fought to answer. Draupadi is sent for, and when she refuses to come quietly she is dragged into the assembly by Dushasana, by the hair, a queen hauled before the court in a single garment. She does not weep and submit; she argues. She puts a question to the hall that no one in it can answer: Yudhishthira staked and lost himself *before* he staked her — so as a man who was already no longer free, by what right did he wager her at all? The elders who should rule on it sit silent. Bhishma, asked directly, can only say that the law of property and the law of the self are subtle and he cannot tell which governs here — the great patriarch reduced to a shrug at the one moment his authority is needed.

Into that silence Dushasana reaches to strip her, and the epic gives its most famous miracle: as he pulls, the cloth does not end, unwinding endlessly however much he tears away, until he collapses exhausted and she stands unshamed — a rescue the text leaves to be read as Krishna's unseen hand. And into the same silence Bhima pours the oaths that will structure the next eighteen days: to break the thigh Duryodhana slaps in invitation, to drink the blood of the Dushasana who dared this. The hall, which came to watch a game, has become the scene of a crime that cannot be taken back.

Blind Dhritarashtra, frightened at last by the omens howling around the palace, tries to unmake it. He grants Draupadi boons, and with them the freedom of her husbands and the return of all they lost, and for a moment it seems the disaster might be walked back. But Duryodhana cannot let them leave restored, and pushes his father into one more throw — a single game, its stake not wealth but exile: the losers to spend twelve years in the forest and a thirteenth in hiding, and if they are recognized in that last year, to begin the whole term again. Yudhishthira, bound as ever, plays, and loses as ever. The Pandavas strip off their royal cloth for bark and deerskin and walk out of Hastinapura into the forest, and the next chapter is the thirteen years that promise buys — years in which the wronged party spends its exile turning itself into something that can finally collect the debt.`,
