    relatedEventSlugs: ["the-exile-and-disguise"],
    bodyMarkdown: `The terms of the second game are precise and cruel: twelve years in the forest, and a thirteenth spent somewhere in the open without being recognized. Slip up in that final year — be identified before it ends — and the whole thirteen begin again. So the exile is not one hardship but two, a long stretch of privation followed by a year of holding one's breath. The Pandavas take both, and the forest years, for all their hardship, become the time when the wronged brothers quietly turn themselves into the force that will one day collect.

The centre of that is Arjuna. Sent by his brothers to win the weapons a war against Hastinapura will require, he undertakes fierce austerities in the mountains and is tested by Shiva himself, who comes disguised as a wild hunter, a kirata, and fights him to a standstill over a contested kill. When Arjuna realizes whom he has been struggling against, the god, pleased, gives him the Pashupata — the most terrible weapon in the epic's arsenal — and other gods give others, so that Arjuna comes back down from the heights carrying an armoury no ordinary warrior can answer. The exile that was meant to break the Pandavas is, in the background, arming them.

The forest also tests them in a register the war never will. In one of the epic's most quietly famous episodes, the brothers one by one drink from a lake against the warning of its guardian spirit, a yaksha, and fall dead where they stand — all but Yudhishthira, who stays to answer the spirit's questions before he drinks. The riddles are not about weapons or tactics but about how to live: what is the greatest wonder, what makes a man truly happy, what is the path. Yudhishthira answers them well enough that the yaksha — his own father Dharma in disguise, testing him — restores his brothers and blesses him. It is the moral counterweight to Arjuna's Pashupata: one brother gathering the means to win a war, another being reminded what a person is supposed to be while he does.

Then the hardest year, the thirteenth, when they must vanish in plain sight. They take service, disguised, in the court of King Virata of the Matsya kingdom: Yudhishthira as a brahmin courtier and companion at dice, Bhima as the palace cook, Arjuna — improbably, and to the epic's evident delight — as Brihannala, a teacher of dance and music living as a eunuch, the great archer hiding inside the one role no one would suspect. The twins keep the king's horses and cattle; Draupadi, who has been a queen and an empress, takes the lowest place of all, as Sairandhri, a maid to Virata's queen. For a year they are no one, and it nearly holds.

It nearly does not, twice. Virata's brutal general Kichaka fixes on the disguised Draupadi and will not be refused, and the danger is only ended when Bhima, breaking cover just far enough, kills him in the dark and leaves the court to wonder what manner of servant did it. And at the very end of the year, the Kauravas — probing for the Pandavas, or simply raiding — drive off Virata's cattle, and the crisis forces Arjuna to take up the Gandiva in the kingdom's defence and scatter an army single-handed, revealing exactly who Virata's dance-teacher has been. But by then the thirteenth year has run its course; the term is served, in full and to the letter. The Pandavas step back into the open as themselves, weapons won and word kept, and send to Hastinapura for what was promised: their kingdom, returned. The next chapter is the answer they get — Krishna riding north to ask for peace, and the refusal that turns thirteen years of patience into the war this whole history has been walking toward.`,
