    relatedEventSlugs: ["krishnas-peace-embassy"],
    bodyMarkdown: `The thirteen years are served, in full and to the letter, and the Pandavas ask for what the terms always promised: their kingdom back. What follows is the part of the story most easily forgotten under the weight of the war it precedes — the long, sincere, and doomed effort to prevent it. Nobody who matters actually wants this war. Bhishma does not want it; Drona does not want it; Vidura pleads against it; even Dhritarashtra, asked plainly, would rather it not happen. The war comes anyway, because one man will not be moved, and everyone else defers to him.

Krishna himself rides to Hastinapura as the Pandavas' envoy, and the demand he carries has shrunk almost to nothing. Not the empire of the Rajasuya, not even the half-kingdom of Indraprastha — just five villages, one for each brother, a settlement so modest it is really only a way of letting Duryodhana keep the peace without quite admitting he was wrong. Duryodhana's answer is the line that has outlived almost everything else in the story: he will not give the Pandavas as much land as would balance on the point of a needle, not without war. And he means it as pride, not calculation — he would rather fight than be seen to yield.

He goes further, and worse. Rather than hear the envoy out, Duryodhana plots to seize Krishna in the middle of the embassy — to arrest the ambassador, which even by the standards of this court is a violation of everything. The attempt collapses; the epic has Krishna reveal, for a moment, that he is not a man who can be bound by ropes at all, and he leaves the hall with the peace formally, finally dead. Both sides begin to call in their allies, and the strange bargain that defines the war is struck: Krishna offers each cousin a choice between his vast army and his own single, unarmed self, and Duryodhana eagerly takes the army while Arjuna takes Krishna — who will not lift a weapon, but will hold the reins of Arjuna's chariot.

Before the lines are drawn, though, the epic pauses on the man the whole war will turn on without knowing it. Krishna goes privately to Karna and tells him the truth of his birth — that he is Kunti's firstborn, the eldest of the Pandavas, and that if he crosses over he could have not five villages but the empire itself, with his younger brothers at his side. And Karna refuses. He knows it is true; he simply will not abandon Duryodhana, the one man who lifted him up when the world laughed, and he will not trade the identity he was shamed into for the one that was hidden from him. He chooses his friend and his fate with open eyes.

Then Kunti herself comes to the son she set adrift, and asks — not for the throne, but for her other children's lives. Karna gives her a terrible, exact mercy: he will not kill any of her sons but Arjuna. Between him and Arjuna one of them must die, that is fixed; but whichever way it falls, Kunti will still have five sons living when the smoke clears, because he counts himself among them now for the first and only time. It is the epic at its most devastating — a mother and her eldest son meeting once, honestly, on the eve of the battle that will end with one of her children killing another, both of them knowing it. The armies are gathering at Kurukshetra. The next chapter is the moment before the first blow, when a different son of Kunti drops his bow.`,
