    relatedEventSlugs: ["bhagavad-gita"],
    bodyMarkdown: `*Dharmakshetre kurukshetre* — on the field of dharma, at Kurukshetra. That is how the Bhagavad Gita opens, and it is where this story begins too: not with a monster or a magic weapon, but with a plain of dry earth outside a city, and two armies who have run out of other options.

Thirteen years earlier, a game of dice had already decided most of what would happen here. Yudhishthira, eldest of the five Pandava brothers and by most accounts the most scrupulously honest man in the story, sat down to play against his cousin Duryodhana's uncle Shakuni — and lost everything. His kingdom. His brothers, staked and lost like coins. Finally Draupadi, wife to all five Pandavas, staked and lost in turn, then dragged into the assembled court while the elders who should have stopped it sat in silence.

Thirteen years of exile followed. When it ended, Krishna — kinsman to both sides, and by the time this story reaches him already a king in his own right — rode to Hastinapura as the Pandavas' envoy, offering Duryodhana a settlement almost embarrassingly small: five villages, one for each brother, in place of the kingdom that was rightfully theirs. Duryodhana's answer has survived, almost word for word, for a very long time: he would not yield land enough to fit on the point of a needle, not without war.

So: two armies, at Kurukshetra. On one side stand the five Pandava brothers and their allies. On the other, Duryodhana's forces — commanded, in a detail the epic dwells on with real discomfort, by Bhishma, the Pandavas' own grand-uncle, a man who raised them, and who is bound by an old vow of loyalty to whoever sits on the Kuru throne. Teachers face students. Grandfathers face grandsons. This is not a war against a foreign enemy; it is a family finishing an argument it could not finish any other way.

It is Arjuna — the Pandavas' finest archer, a man who has never in the story lost his nerve in battle — who asks Krishna to drive their chariot into the gap between the two armies, so he can see who he is about to fight. And it is there, looking at the faces of people who raised him, taught him, and loved him, that his bow slips from his hands.

What Krishna says to him next does not stay on the battlefield. It becomes its own text, recited on its own terms for thousands of years afterward, regardless of what anyone believes about chariots or gods: the Bhagavad Gita, the Song of the Lord.

Krishna's answer works on Arjuna's despair from several sides at once. He begins with the self: what is essential in a person is not the body that dies but something imperishable — unborn, undying, that no weapon cuts and no fire burns — so the grief that cries *I will be the one who destroys these men* mistakes the perishable part for the whole. Then he turns to duty: Arjuna is a warrior, and the fight in front of him is a just one he did not seek; to walk away from it now, out of a faintness of heart dressed up as compassion, would be its own failure of dharma. But the core of the teaching is subtler than *fight anyway*. It is that action cannot be escaped by refusing to act — even sitting down is a choice with consequences — and so the discipline is to act without grasping after the fruits: to do what is right because it is right, and surrender the outcome, neither inflated by success nor destroyed by failure. Krishna offers more than one road to that freedom — the way of selfless action, the way of knowledge, and the way of devotion, of offering everything one does back to the divine — and insists they arrive at the same place.

When Arjuna asks to see who is really counselling him, Krishna shows him: the Vishwarupa, the cosmic form, in which Arjuna beholds all worlds and all beings at once, the warriors of both armies already pouring into a vast devouring mouth, and hears the sentence that has long outlived its setting — that Krishna is time, the destroyer of worlds, and that in a sense these men are already slain, the outcome already decided; Arjuna is asked not to author it but to be its instrument. It is a vision that terrifies at least as much as it consoles, and Arjuna, shaken and steadied both, takes up the bow he had let fall. The despair that opened the war is answered — not by making the killing painless, but by changing what Arjuna understands himself to be doing. Then the conches sound, and the war he tried to refuse begins in earnest.`,
