    relatedEventSlugs: ["fall-of-bhishma"],
    bodyMarkdown: `When the fighting begins in earnest, it runs into a wall named Bhishma. The grandfather commands the Kaurava army, and he is, by the terms the epic has set up, very close to unkillable: granted long ago the boon of choosing the hour of his own death, he cannot be taken down against his will, and no one on the field can match him. For ten days he cuts through the Pandava host, and the awful thing about it is that he does not want to. He is fighting his own grandsons, the boys he raised, on behalf of a throne his vow bound him to defend — killing people he loves, at half his heart, and still no one can stop him.

The Pandavas reach a kind of despair that has nothing to do with courage. They are not losing their nerve; they are losing the war, to a man who is grieving every blow he lands. And so they do the strangest thing the war will ask of them: they go, at night, to Bhishma's own tent, and ask him how he can be killed. It is a measure of what Bhishma has become — a man trapped inside his own invincibility, fighting a cause he despises for a vow he will not break — that he answers them. He tells them the way out, because he wants one too.

The key is an old wound the epic planted generations ago. Bhishma holds a vow never to raise a weapon against a woman, or against one he regards as born a woman — and in the Pandava ranks stands exactly such a figure: Shikhandi, born to Drupada, and carrying within a past life the soul of Amba, the bride Bhishma abducted and discarded, who has spent a lifetime and a death arranging to be here for this. Bhishma knows who Shikhandi is. That is the point. The instrument of his death is the grievance he created with his own hands, come back grown and armed.

On the tenth day, Arjuna advances with Shikhandi before him, and Bhishma, seeing Amba's vengeance arrive in the form he swore never to strike, lowers his bow. He does not fight. He lets it happen. Arjuna — sheltered behind that refusal, and hating it — fills the old man with so many arrows that when Bhishma finally falls, he does not reach the ground: he lies suspended on the shafts themselves, a bed of arrows, the most famous image the war produces. It is not a clean victory and no one pretends it is. The Pandavas have won by asking their enemy to arrange his own death, and their enemy agreed because living was worse.

And then Bhishma does the last thing his boon allows. He chooses not to die. Held up off the earth on that bed of arrows, he elects to linger — postponing his death for weeks, until the sun turns north at the winter solstice and the hour is auspicious — and from there, dying and not dead, he watches the rest of the war play out and dispenses counsel to whoever will come and listen. His fall is the first of the great pillars to go, and it takes the war's last restraint with it: the man both sides revered is down, by a trick that was really a mercy, and after Bhishma there is no one left whom everyone still obeys. Command of the Kaurava army passes to Drona, and the war stops slowing down. The next chapter is where it takes its cruelest turn yet, against a boy of sixteen.`,
