    relatedEventSlugs: ["death-of-abhimanyu"],
    bodyMarkdown: `By the war's thirteenth day, the Gita is thirteen days in the past and mostly irrelevant to what is happening on the ground. Bhishma has already fallen, ten days in, lowering his weapons rather than fight from behind Shikhandi. The war has stopped being a discussion about duty and started being a machine that consumes a fixed number of days and a much larger number of people.

On day thirteen, the Kaurava general Drona sets a trap built entirely out of geometry. He arrays his army in a Chakravyuha — a spiral formation, the kind that lets a smaller force fight a bottleneck instead of a battlefield — and only a handful of warriors on either side know the sequence of moves required to fight into its center. Fewer still know how to fight back out.

Arjuna is one of the ones who knows both halves. But Arjuna is not there; he has been drawn off to the far edge of the field by a separate, engineered distraction, exactly as Drona intended. Which leaves Abhimanyu — Arjuna's son, sixteen years old by most tellings, married only recently to Uttara — as the only Pandava warrior who knows how to get in.

He knows it secondhand. The story the epic tells is that he heard his father describe the sequence while he was still in his mother Subhadra's womb — and that Subhadra fell asleep, or was interrupted, before Arjuna got to the part about getting back out. It is the kind of detail that sounds like folklore and is repeated anyway, because it captures something true about what's about to happen: a boy with exactly half the knowledge he needs, sent in anyway, because the army needs the formation broken and he is the only one who can break it.

He breaks it. That part works. He fights into the center of the Chakravyuha alone, and the elder Pandavas, blocked at the entrance by Jayadratha, cannot follow him in. What happens next is not one warrior beating him in a duel — the epic is specific that it takes several, converging on him at once, in a fight that by the war's own rules should have stayed one-on-one. He dies in the center of a formation he was only ever taught how to enter.

Yudhishthira and Arjuna are the ones who have to sit with what that means: that the code the whole war was supposedly fought to uphold — dharma, fairness, the rules of a righteous fight — did not hold at the one moment it mattered most for their own son. The next chapter is the war finishing what it started, but it starts from here, from a boy who knew half the way out, and a promise about fair combat that the winning side broke first.`,
