    relatedEventSlugs: ["jayadrathas-death"],
    bodyMarkdown: `Arjuna comes back to the camp on the evening of the thirteenth day and learns that his son is dead — and, worse, how. Abhimanyu did not fall in an honest defeat. He fell inside a formation he alone could open, while the rest of the Pandavas were held out at its mouth, unable to follow him in, by a single man planted there for exactly that purpose. The man's name is Jayadratha, and by morning Arjuna's grief has narrowed to him.

Jayadratha is king of Sindhu, and married into the enemy: his wife is Dushala, the hundred-and-first child of Dhritarashtra and Gandhari, the Kauravas' only sister. His grudge against the Pandavas is older than the war. During the exile he had tried to carry Draupadi off from the forest, been run down by the brothers, and — rather than killed — spared with his head shaved bald, humiliated instead of executed. He never forgave it, and he prayed to Shiva for the power to answer it, receiving a narrow boon: for a single day, he could hold off four of the five Pandavas, all but Arjuna. On the thirteenth day he spent that one day's gift at the mouth of the Chakravyuha, and it cost Abhimanyu his life.

So Arjuna swears an oath more dangerous to himself than to any enemy: he will kill Jayadratha before the sun sets on the fourteenth day, or he will walk into a fire and burn. The Kauravas hear the vow and understand precisely what it gives them. They do not have to defeat Arjuna tomorrow; they only have to keep one man breathing until sundown, and Arjuna will do the rest to himself. So the whole of day fourteen becomes a single tactic — hide Jayadratha behind the deepest part of the army, and run out the clock.

It nearly works. Arjuna cuts through formation after formation all day and cannot reach the man in time; the sun slides down the sky with the vow unkept, and across the field the pyre for Arjuna's own death is being built. And then Krishna, who will not raise a weapon but will bend the heavens, brings on a false dusk — the epic tells it as an illusion, or as the sun truly veiled — and the light fails early. The Kaurava lines erupt in relief, certain it is over, and Jayadratha himself comes forward out of his hiding to watch Arjuna climb onto the fire. And the sun comes back.

Krishna says: now. And there is one last snare in it, because Jayadratha's father held a boon that whoever made his son's head fall to the ground would have his own head burst apart. So Arjuna does not simply take the head — he looses his arrows to catch it and carry it off the field entirely, away over the lines, and set it down in the lap of the old father sitting far off in his evening prayers. The startled man rises; the head rolls from his lap to the earth; and his own head shatters, the curse rebounding onto the one who laid it. Jayadratha is dead, the vow kept, Abhimanyu half-answered — and answered, like every reckoning in this war, by a trick rather than a fair blow. But the fourteenth day is not finished, because the sun has set for real now, and the fighting does not stop.`,
