    bodyMarkdown: `The fourteenth day refuses to end. Enraged by Jayadratha's death, Drona keeps the armies fighting on past dark into the war's one great night battle — fought by torchlight, in a confusion where men kill men they cannot see. And into that darkness the Pandavas send something the Kauravas have no answer for.

His name is Ghatotkacha, and he is Bhima's son. Long before, in the Pandavas' first desperate wanderings after they escaped the house of lac, Bhima had killed a man-eating rakshasa in the forest and then married the rakshasa's sister, Hidimba; she bore him a son who grew to his full strength in a single day, as his mother's kind do, and then went his own way, promising only to come when his father had need of him. Half-human and half-rakshasa, Ghatotkacha can do in the dark exactly what no mortal soldier can — and this is the need, and this is the dark.

Summoned into the night, he is a catastrophe. He grows vast, throws illusions, spreads terror, and tears through the Kaurava host until it becomes plain that if nothing stops him there may be no Kaurava army left to see the dawn. Duryodhana, frantic, turns to the one man who might still have something in reserve: Karna.

And Karna does — the single most precious thing he owns. Indra had once given him the Vasavi Shakti, a dart that cannot miss and cannot fail to kill whatever it strikes, and that can be used exactly once. Karna has carried it untouched through the entire war, hoarded against one purpose only: Arjuna, the one man he fears he cannot beat, the brother fate has aimed him at. To throw it at Ghatotkacha is to spend, on a rakshasa in the dark, the one certain means he had of killing Arjuna. But the alternative is to lose the army tonight, and so he throws it. The dart takes Ghatotkacha through the chest and kills him instantly — and the dying giant does one last thing, swelling to the size of a hill and toppling, so that his own falling body crushes a whole division of Kaurava troops beneath it.

The Pandava camp fills with grief, and Bhima is inconsolable. And Krishna, to the horror of everyone watching, laughs — embraces Arjuna, and by some accounts dances for joy. Because Krishna has been carrying one fear through the whole war: that as long as Karna held that infallible dart, Arjuna was a dead man the moment the two finally met. Now the dart is gone, spent in the dark on a nephew, and Arjuna will live. Ghatotkacha's death has bought his uncle's life, and Krishna, who does this arithmetic without ever flinching from it, will not pretend to grieve a trade that just won the war. It is one of the coldest and clearest windows the epic ever opens onto what Krishna actually is. By morning it is the fifteenth day, and the war comes at last for its second great teacher.`,
