    relatedEventSlugs: ["fall-of-drona"],
    bodyMarkdown: `By the fifteenth day Bhishma is down, Abhimanyu and Jayadratha are dead, and the night battle has taken Ghatotkacha — and still Drona commands the Kaurava army, the war's own teacher become its most dangerous instrument. He trained nearly every great warrior on both fields; there is little they can do that he did not teach them, and while he holds his bow he cannot be beaten in open combat. The Pandavas are once again facing a wall, and once again the only way through it is not strength but the exploiting of a love.

Drona's love is his son, Ashwatthama. It is the one thing that can reach past the warrior to the man, and Krishna, who has stopped pretending this war can be won cleanly, proposes to use it. The plan is a lie with a trapdoor built into it: on the field, Bhima kills an elephant that happens to bear the name Ashwatthama, and then raises his voice to announce that Ashwatthama is dead. Drona hears it, and does not believe it — his son is not a creature that dies easily — and he turns to the one man in either army whose word he trusts absolutely, because that man has never in his life told a lie: Yudhishthira.

Everything the epic has built around Yudhishthira comes due in this single moment. He is asked, directly, by his own teacher, whether Ashwatthama is dead — and he is asked to choose between the truth he has staked his entire identity on and the victory his brothers and his cause depend on. He says it: "Ashwatthama is dead." And then, unable to make himself lie outright, he adds, under his breath — or drowned out, in the telling, by Krishna's conch and the war-drums raised for exactly this purpose — "the elephant." It is true. It is also a lie, and Yudhishthira knows it is, and the epic marks the cost with a detail it has been saving: his chariot, which had always ridden a little above the ground because of his truthfulness, settles down onto the earth. The one man who could not lie has lied, and the world registers it instantly.

Drona hears only the first three words. Believing his son dead, the old teacher lays down his weapons in the middle of the battle, sinks down in grief and meditation, and stops fighting. And Dhrishtadyumna — Draupadi's fire-born brother, brought into the world for precisely this, the death of Drona — steps up to the disarmed, mourning man and strikes off his head. It is murder of a kind the rules of the war forbid twice over: a warrior killed while unarmed, undone by a lie about his child. The second great pillar has fallen, and like the first, it fell not to skill but to a broken rule.

By now a pattern is visible that the epic wants no one to miss. Bhishma was brought down by a vow used against him; Drona by a lie and a blade taken to an unarmed man. Each time, the Pandavas — the side of dharma, the righteous side — win by breaking exactly the kind of rule the war was supposed to be fought to defend. The victories are real and they are also stains, and the epic keeps a running account of them, because it intends to present the bill later. Command of what is left of the Kaurava army now passes, at last, to Karna. But before the two great archers can finally meet, the war turns to collecting the Pandavas' oldest debts — beginning with the oath Bhima swore, in the gambling hall thirteen years ago, over Dushasana.`,
