    relatedEventSlugs: ["death-of-dushasana"],
    bodyMarkdown: `With Drona gone and Karna in command, the war enters its final and ugliest phase — the days when it stops producing victories and starts settling accounts. Most of the accounts are Bhima's, and the oldest and worst of them was opened thirteen years earlier, in the gambling hall, on the afternoon the dice game curdled into something that could never be undone.

It is worth going back to that hall for a moment, because this chapter is its answer. When Dushasana dragged Draupadi in by the hair and set about pulling the single garment from her before the silent, staring court, Bhima had sworn two things aloud, and the room had gone quiet at the sound of them. He swore to break the thigh Duryodhana bared to her. And he swore to tear open Dushasana's chest and drink his blood. For thirteen years — through exile, through the failed peace, through fifteen days of war — those two oaths have sat inside the story like loaded weapons waiting for a hand.

On the sixteenth day, Bhima finds Dushasana in the churn of the field, and the epic does not flinch from what keeping such an oath actually looks like. He strikes him down, breaks open his chest with his hands, and — in the account the text gives without softening — drinks, or smears himself with, the blood, roaring that it tastes sweeter than his mother's milk, sweeter than honey, sweeter than anything he has known. It is not staged as clean justice. It is staged as a horror, and it is meant to be one: hardened men on Bhima's own side turn away, and some simply flee the sight of it.

And yet it is, precisely, a promise kept. Everything Draupadi endured in that hall — the fist in her hair, the hand at her clothing, the elders who studied the floor rather than look at her — is being answered here, thirteen years late, in the only coin Bhima ever named for it. Draupadi, who has carried that afternoon unhealed through everything since, has her grievance paid at last. The epic lets both truths stand at once and refuses to dissolve either into the other: that the debt was real and owed, and that the paying of it is monstrous to watch.

One of Bhima's two hall-oaths is now discharged. The other — the thigh — is still waiting, being kept, whether Bhima thinks of it that way or not, for the very last man left standing. But that reckoning is two deaths off yet. First the war has to give the story the one duel it has withheld since the beginning: the two sons of Kunti, who were never told they were brothers, finally facing each other across the field.`,
