    relatedEventSlugs: ["death-of-karna"],
    bodyMarkdown: `Karna takes command, and the epic finally lets the two men it has kept apart come together: Karna and Arjuna, the two greatest archers alive, matched at last with nothing left between them but the field. The reader carries into it the knowledge neither brother fully shares — that these are Kunti's two sons, the abandoned firstborn and the favoured third, and that the war has been arranging this particular killing from the moment a basket went into a river a lifetime ago.

It is not a fair fight, and the unfairness runs against Karna, which is the epic's bitter joke on a man whose whole life was decided by an accident of birth. Every debt he ever incurred comes due at once. A curse from his own teacher, earned for a lie he told about his caste in order to be taught at all, ensures that the incantation for his mightiest weapon deserts him the instant he most needs it. A brahmin's curse, laid on him years before, ensures that at the fatal moment his chariot wheel sinks and jams in the earth. He had already given away the divine armour he was born wearing — and the one infallible weapon that might have settled the duel in a single throw, the dart he had hoarded all war to use on Arjuna, is gone too, spent two nights before on Ghatotkacha when nothing else could stop him. He is, at the decisive instant, the most capable man on the field and the most comprehensively disarmed by his own past.

The wheel sinks. Karna, weaponless for a moment and struggling to free it, appeals to Arjuna by the very code the war keeps invoking and breaking — the rule that you do not strike a man who is unarmed and off his chariot — and asks him to hold, to wait, to let him lift the wheel and resume the duel fairly. And Krishna, at Arjuna's shoulder, answers before Arjuna can. He asks Karna, coldly, where that code was when they surrounded Abhimanyu; where it was when Draupadi was dragged into the hall; where the rules were on every day the Kauravas needed them gone. Then he tells Arjuna to shoot. And Arjuna, hesitating, does — killing Karna as he wrestles with the wheel, hands empty, the fairness he asked for refused him exactly as he once helped refuse it to others.

Only Krishna and Kunti know, as Karna falls, what has just happened in full: that Arjuna has killed his own elder brother, and that he did it without being told, because the telling was kept from him until it was too late to matter. Kunti had one meeting with her firstborn and spent it securing the lives of her other children; Krishna had known the secret the whole time and let the war carry it to this conclusion. Arjuna will learn, after everything is over, whom he killed at the wheel — and it will be one of the griefs he cannot put down.

The epic does not let anyone celebrate Karna's death, and it does not let the reader hate him. Of all the people the war consumes, Karna is the one it treats as most sinned against — loyal past all reason, generous to a fault, shamed for a birth he never chose and then killed by the breaking of the one rule that might have saved him. His death effectively ends the Kaurava war effort; there is no one of his stature left. What remains is the man the whole thing was always really about — Duryodhana, now nearly alone — and the last duel, in which the winning side breaks its final rule. That is the next chapter.`,
