    relatedEventSlugs: ["death-of-duryodhana"],
    bodyMarkdown: `By the eighteenth day there is almost no one left to command. Karna is dead; Dushasana died two days before him, torn open to answer Bhima's oldest oath; Shakuni, the architect of the whole ruin, is dead at the hands of Sahadeva; Shalya at Yudhishthira's; ninety-nine of the hundred brothers are gone, most of them to Bhima, who swore that too. The army Duryodhana raised to outnumber his cousins has been spent down to almost nothing, and the war has arrived, as it was always going to, at him.

And Duryodhana — the man who would not yield a needle's point of land — runs. He flees the field alone and hides at the bottom of a lake, using a last magic to hold the waters still around himself, the crown prince of the Kurus submerged and silent while the wreckage of everything he wanted settles above him. The Pandavas find him there and taunt him out; he will not die hiding, whatever else he is, and he comes up to fight. He agrees to a single duel, one weapon, and he chooses the mace, and he chooses Bhima.

Here the epic springs a discomfort it has been setting up all along: in a fair mace fight, Duryodhana may well be the better man. He is a superb mace-fighter, trained by Balarama himself, and evenly matched with Bhima or better. The two of them fight to exhaustion, and it is not at all clear that righteousness is going to win on skill. What decides it is not skill. Bhima has an oath — sworn in that same poisoned hall years ago — to break the thigh Duryodhana bared and slapped in invitation to Draupadi. And a blow below the waist is forbidden in mace combat, one of the clearest rules the duel has. Krishna, watching, slaps his own thigh in silent signal, and Bhima strikes low, shattering Duryodhana's thighs and dropping him to the ground.

It is a foul, and everyone present knows it is a foul. Balarama, Krishna's own brother and Duryodhana's teacher, is enraged enough to leave. And Duryodhana, broken-legged and dying slowly in the dirt, is given by the epic the most uncomfortable speech in the whole war — because he is, on the narrow point, right. He lists it all: Bhishma brought down from behind a warrior he was sworn not to fight, Drona killed disarmed and grieving over a lie, Karna shot while lifting his stuck wheel, himself felled by a blow below the belt. Every one of the great Kaurava deaths came by a broken rule, and every rule was broken by the side that called itself dharma. He dies insisting he fought clean and lost dirty — and the epic, pointedly, has the gods rain flowers on his corpse, as if to concede he is not simply wrong.

The Pandavas have won. The kingdom is theirs; the cousin who would not share it is dying at their feet; the thing they fought thirteen years and eighteen days for is, finally, accomplished. And the epic refuses to let it feel like victory. It has spent the whole war keeping accounts, and the ledger it hands over now is filthy on every line — a war for dharma won by the steady abandonment of dharma, a throne cleared of every rival at the cost of nearly every kinsman on earth. What the next act deals with is not triumph but the bill: a night raid that answers the foul with a worse one, a mother's curse, and the long, grey question of what exactly was won.`,
