    relatedFigureSlugs: ["ashwatthama", "draupadi", "dhrishtadyumna", "krishna"],
    relatedEventSlugs: ["ashwatthamas-night-raid"],
    bodyMarkdown: `The war is won, and it is not finished. Duryodhana lies on the field with his thighs broken, dying slowly through the last evening, and to him comes the one man still standing who loved him — Ashwatthama, Drona's son, half-mad with grief at the lie that killed his father and the foul that felled his friend. Duryodhana, with almost his last breath, makes him the commander of an army that no longer exists, and asks him for the only thing left to want: vengeance. Ashwatthama swears it, and the swearing is the last thing Duryodhana hears.

That night, the Pandavas are not in their camp. Krishna, for reasons the epic lets you read as foresight, had drawn them away to spend the night elsewhere, by the river. So when Ashwatthama comes through the dark with two companions, what he finds is not his enemies but everyone who belonged to them, asleep in the certainty that the war is over and the killing is done. And he kills them all. He kills Dhrishtadyumna — the man who beheaded his father — not with a warrior's sword but with his hands and feet, denying him even the death of a soldier. He kills Shikhandi. He kills, in the dark, the five young sons of Draupadi and the Pandavas, the entire next generation, cut down asleep in a single night. Then he burns the camp and is gone before dawn.

When the Pandavas return in the morning, the victory of the day before has become something the language of victory cannot hold. They walked off that field having lost almost everyone on the other side; they walk back onto it having lost almost everyone on their own — their allies, their commander, and their children, murdered in their sleep in an act that answers the war's every broken rule with a final, total one. Draupadi, who has already lost her father and her brothers, now loses all five of her sons in one stroke, and her grief turns to a single demand: that Ashwatthama be brought to answer for it.

The pursuit that follows nearly ends the world rather than one man. Cornered, Ashwatthama looses a celestial weapon — a Brahmastra, the kind of arm that does not kill a person but a lineage, a region, a future — and Arjuna is forced to raise its twin to meet it. Two such weapons loosed against each other would scorch everything, and the sages who appear command both archers to withdraw them. Arjuna, pure enough to have earned the weapon, can call his back. Ashwatthama cannot — and, told to redirect it somewhere, he aims it with deliberate malice at the last thing the Pandavas have left: the womb of Uttara, Abhimanyu's widow, carrying the only unborn heir of the entire line.

For that, Krishna hands down the epic's harshest sentence, and it is not death. Ashwatthama is cursed to live — to wander the earth for thousands of years, alone, his wound never healing, festering and unloved, a deathless exile who will envy every corpse the war produced. And Krishna reaches into the ruined womb and restores the child the weapon killed, so that the Kuru line, burned down to a single unborn ember, does not quite go out: the boy will be born, and named Parikshit, and one day be king. That thread of continuity is all the mercy the night raid leaves. Everything else is ash — and the next chapter is the survivors standing in it, counting what victory actually cost.`,
