    relatedEventSlugs: ["sorrow-of-victory"],
    bodyMarkdown: `When the fighting is finally, wholly over, the epic does something most war stories avoid: it stops, and turns the whole of its attention to the women who come out onto the field to find their dead. This is the part the poem calls the Book of the Women, and it is the closest the Mahabharata comes to stating its own verdict — a plain of corpses stretching to the horizon, and among them the mothers and widows of both sides, indistinguishable now in their grief, searching the faces.

At the centre of it is Gandhari, who bound her own eyes for a lifetime rather than see more than her blind husband could, and who now, by the grace or curse of the moment, sees everything: her hundred sons dead, the flower of two houses rotting in the sun, the total sum of what pride and patience and cleverness produced. And she turns on Krishna — not on Duryodhana, not on fate, but on the one being present who could have stopped it and chose instead to let it run to the end. She curses him: that he who stood by while the Kuru house destroyed itself will watch his own people, the Yadavas, tear themselves apart in a drunken brawl, and will die alone and ignobly, a nobody's arrow in the greatest of them. And Krishna bows his head and accepts it, because he did let it run, and he has never claimed otherwise.

Then the grief turns and finds the victors where they are weakest. Kunti, unable to carry it into old age, finally tells her five sons the thing she has kept since a riverbank long before any of them were born: that Karna — the man they mocked as a charioteer's son, the enemy Arjuna shot at the wheel, the warrior they spent their whole lives hating and fearing — was her firstborn, and their own eldest brother. The knowledge lands on them like a second war. They have killed their brother, honoured his killer among themselves, and mourned him too late to matter; and Yudhishthira, who has borne more of this than any of them, turns his anguish into a curse of his own — that no woman, ever after, will be able to hold a secret — the helpless fury of a man who has just learned that the one secret that might have prevented everything was kept from him out of love.

So Yudhishthira is crowned. It is the thing the entire epic has driven toward — the rightful, righteous king on the Kuru throne at last — and the poem stages it as one of the saddest scenes it has. He takes a kingdom emptied of its whole warrior generation, ruled over a silence where a hundred cousins and countless allies used to be, and he does it half-refusing, sick with the cost, having to be argued out of simply walking away into the forest to atone. He performs the rites for the dead — including, now, for the brother he did not know he had — and he governs well and joylessly, a good king reigning over the proof that winning and being right are not the same thing.

The victory is total and it is ash, exactly as the epic kept promising it would be. But a crown is not the same as peace, and Yudhishthira cannot simply set the war down — first he has to be taught how to carry it. That teaching is waiting for him at the edge of the battlefield, where the one man the war left standing long enough to give it still lies on his bed of arrows.`,
