    relatedEventSlugs: ["great-departure"],
    bodyMarkdown: `The last movement comes years later, and it begins with Krishna's own end — exactly as Gandhari swore it would. The Yadavas, his own people, fall to drinking and old grudges and destroy themselves in a single ruinous brawl, and Krishna, the still point at the centre of the whole epic, dies alone in a forest of a hunter's stray arrow, mistaken for a deer — the same accidental death by which this history's troubles so often arrive. With him gone, the age itself turns; the world tips into the Kali Yuga, the last and worst of the ages, and the Pandavas understand that their time is finished.

Yudhishthira sets the crown on the head of Parikshit — Abhimanyu's son, the child killed in the womb and restored, the single ember the war left of the whole line — and then the five brothers and Draupadi do the thing this family has always, finally, done: they give it all up. They take off their royal cloth, turn their backs on Hastinapura, and set out on foot toward the north, toward the high Himalayas and the gates of heaven, seeking to walk out of the world bodily rather than die in it. A dog falls in beside them on the road and follows, and no one sends it away.

They climb, and one by one they fall. Draupadi drops first, and Bhima, grieving, asks why — she who did no wrong. Yudhishthira, walking ahead without turning, answers plainly: she loved Arjuna more than the rest, and that partiality is the flaw she carries out of the world. Then Sahadeva falls, for his pride in his own wisdom; then Nakula, for his pride in his beauty; then Arjuna, for the vanity of the great archer who swore to burn his enemies in a day and did not; then Bhima, for his pride in his strength and his appetite. Each time, Yudhishthira names the fault and keeps walking, refusing to stop, refusing to grieve, because the ascent does not allow looking back — and because the poem is making its last argument, that even these five, the near-perfect and the divinely fathered, each carried something that keeps a person out of heaven whole.

At the end, only Yudhishthira and the dog remain, and Indra's chariot descends to carry him — alive, in his own body, an honour granted to almost no one — up to heaven. There is one condition. He must leave the dog. And Yudhishthira, who once told a single half-lie and felt his chariot drop to the earth for it, refuses the chariot of the gods. He will not enter heaven at the price of abandoning a creature that was faithful to him and asked for nothing; he would rather forfeit paradise than commit that one small betrayal. It is his last test, and it is the whole of him in a sentence — and the dog, of course, is no dog at all, but Dharma, the god of righteousness, his own divine father, who has been walking beside him in disguise to see whether the most righteous man alive would trade loyalty for reward. He would not. He passes.

Even then the epic will not give him a clean arrival — there is a final illusion, a glimpse of his brothers and Draupadi seeming to suffer in a hell he is briefly shown, one last lesson that even the best must taste sorrow and deception before the end — and then it resolves, and the family that tore itself apart over a throne is gathered again beyond the world, the long quarrel finally, wholly over. And there the poem closes the circle it opened so many generations ago: it began with a king on a riverbank who gave up a goddess and watched seven sons carried into the water, and it ends with a king on a mountain who would not give up a stray dog — the whole enormous machinery of dynasty and war and dharma narrowing, at the last, to the simplest question the epic knows how to ask, which is who you are willing to abandon, and who you are not. The Mahabharata says of itself that what is found here is found everywhere, and what is not here is found nowhere; and it ends not in triumph, but in a man refusing, on a cold mountainside, to leave the last loyal thing behind.`,
